You&#39;ll need a _loop_ for each array.

```java
void f(int[][] x) {
    int i, n;
    for (int[] a : x)
        for (i = 0, n = x.length; i &lt; n; i++)
            if (a[i] == 1) a[i] = 7;
}
```

The problem is with this line: `for (int i = 0; i &lt; path.length+1; i++) {`

When I first saw that line, I thought it was iterating through each row of `path`.  But, it causes your program to look for `path.length` *cells*, not rows, then quits. Unless the path is straight down, there are more cells, likely many more, in the path than `path.length`.

I suggest the following changes to your code:

 - Decide on how it will be determined that the end of the path has been reached. 
 - Replace the `for` loop with a `while` loop or a `do while` loop, using the terminating condition. This is because the number of cells to be marked will be unknown when the loop begins.
 - Alternatively, use `while (true)` and have a `break` inside the loop when the terminating condition is reached.
 - Move `path[row][col] = 7` to the top of the loop, before the `if` statements that check if the next move is right, down, or left. Alternatively, move it after those `if` blocks. For simplicity, it is better to have it in one place.
 -  The *only* content of the right / down / left `if` blocks should be to change `row`  or `col`, and possibly to detect the terminating condition.
 - Add guard `if` statements to be sure checking the adjacent cells does not go out of bounds. 

````
boolean advance = true;
int row = 0;
int col = 0;
while ( advance ) { 
    path [row][col] = 7;
    if (path [row][col+1] == 1) { col++; } // right
    else if (path[row][col-1] == 1) { col--; } // left
    else if (path[row+1][col] == 1) { row++; } // down
    else { advance = false; }
}
````

I did not include the guard checking. Without them, this code will throw an `ArrayIndexOutOfBounds` condition for most paths. You can add the guard conditions to the `if` statements using `&amp;&amp;` before the `path[` part.

This code assumes `path [0][0]` will initially have a value of `1`. It assumes there will be no turn in the up direction.

