Note that if you need to use `i.remove();` in your loop, or access the actual iterator in some way, you cannot use the `for ( : )` idiom, since the actual iterator is merely inferred.

As was noted by Denis Bueno, this code works for any object that implements the [`Iterable` interface][1].

Also, if the right-hand side of the `for (:)` idiom is an `array` rather than an `Iterable` object, the internal code uses an int index counter and checks against `array.length` instead. See the [Java Language Specification][2].


